@warmspringwinds can you refactor this to use more functions? Every "paragraph" that you start with a comment explaining its purpose is a candidate for refactoring.

NASA [enforces](http://pixelscommander.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/P10.pdf) that no function should be longer than 60 lines, including variable declarations (one per line). I think we should stick to that — it allows code review having the full function in sight, rather than having to remember what came before.

This comment also applies to `detect_multi_scale`, above.

However, I would change all this quite dramatically, since it takes almost no effort to make this function work on nD images instead of just 2D:

```python
def direct_time(im, psf):
    return np.product(im.shape + psf.shape)
def fft_time(im, psf):
    return sum(k*np.log(k) for k in im.shape + psf.shape)
def time_ratio(im, psf):
    # constant factor obtained by curve fitting, see
    # https://github.com/scikit-image/scikit-image/pull/1792
    return 71.468 * fft_time(im, psf) / direct_time(im, psf)
convolve_function = fftconvolve if time_ratio(im, psf) < 1 else convolve
```
By using the `convolve` function and the more general function definitions, we get nD functionality essentially for free!

The only downside is that the constant factors might change now. =\

The %ignore operator in SWIG tells the parser to ignore any declarations that follow it. Note that I've moved the %include below the ignore, which has the effect of not creating bindings for the declarations of `getActiveCells`, etc. in `TemporalMemory.hpp`. We want this so that SWIG creates bindings for the version of `getActiveCells`, etc. that I defined above, which return lists, rather than the default bindings, which return tuples.

Finding the correct way to override a binding with the same name as that used in C++ took a fair bit of investigation, but I believe that this is the correct approach. In general, the approach is:

```C++
// First you define your bindings function
PyObject* myFunction()
{
  ...
}

// %ignore ignores matching declarations *after* it is called
%ignore myFunction;

// Finally the include needs to be at the end after both the binding definition and the ignore
%include "header.hpp"
```

